#Linux filesystem types. (Ext2, Ext3, Ext4)
-
1 ) **Ext2**

* Ext2 stands for second extended file system.
* Ext2 doesn't have journaling feature.
* On flash memory, it is recommanded.
* Mazimum individual file size can be from 16 GB ~ 2 TB
* Overall ext2 file system size can be from 2 TB ~ 32 TB

2 ) **Ext3**

* Ext3 stands for third extended file system.
* Ext3 allows journaling.
* Journaling has a dedicated area in the file system, where all the changes are tracked. When the system crashes, the possibility of file system corruption is less because of journaling.
* Maximum individual file size can be from 16 GB to 2 TB
* Overall ext3 file system size can be from 2 TB to 32 TB

3 ) **Ext4**

* Ext4 stands for fourth extended file system.
* Supports huge individual file size and overall file system size.
* Maximum individual file size can be from 16 GB to 16 TB
* Overall maximum ext4 file system size is 1 EB (exabyte). 1 EB = 1024 PB (petabyte). 1 PB = 1024 TB (terabyte).
* You can also mount an existing ext3 fs as ext4 fs (without having to upgrade it).